Date:12/19/2006 12:00:54 AM
From:Paul Senior
You are correct on all points, imo. It's that I view SJT differently.

I've never before bought SJT anytime I looked at it over the past 15-20 years.
It's always been a depreciating asset, and that has put me off. (It IS a trust,
not a viable (growing) business.) When its assets are gone, they are not
replaced, and it's all over for SJT. The thing is, over the 15 or so years, the
assets never seem to have disappeared, and the trust paid out a good
distribution. Somehow, this thing continues to survive, apparently okay
(measured by distributions paid). I'm just betting that it will continue to do
okay. Maybe not forever, but maybe for another ten years. Who knows? Maybe it's
a race: its oil is being sold off, but those oil sales might in future be at
higher prices.

I'm increasing the dividend component of a couple of my portfolios, and this
stock fits what I'm looking for: Okay distribution and a shot at price
appreciation if oil rises (and if SJT doesn't run out of it). (aside: I'm not
exactly sure what the SJT payout is called: I believe it's not technically a
'dividend', but I'll use dividend here to mean any scheduled, routine payout or
distribution.)

Perhaps as you say, SJT's not the best bet going, but then I have other oil/gas
plays which will maybe take up the slack.

Aside: I have been hoping that holding oil/gas stocks with decent dividend
yields would be less volatile than oil/gas stocks without significant
dividends. This has not been the case for me. Changes proposed in Canadian
trust laws have made these trusts both losing bets so far, and volatile
performers. Furthermore, it seems to me that the majority of e&p's, integrated
oils, as well as oil service stocks, all move together (like today, where I've
got lots of multi-point losses in a significant number of such positions). So
buying and adding more dividend paying oil/gas stocks to my portfolio(s) hasn't
helped me reduce volatility, which is a goal for me. Indeed, by continuing to
buy these dividend payers and not reduce the others, the composition of the
portfolio is being altered with a heavier weighting of these heavily correlated
stocks, and portfolio volatility has increased. Back on the other hand though,
I recall something about Buffett's "we'd rather have a lumpy 15% than a steady
9%" or words like that. I like that intellectually, not sure I like the
emotional cost to me though. -g-
